    [
        'category'    => 'cms_pages',
        'subcategory' => 'about_us',
        'title'       => 'About Us Page Content Structure',
        'content'     => 'An About Us page is the most-visited non-product page on most e-commerce sites, yet it is frequently treated as an afterthought. Structure it in four sections. First, the Origin Story (100-150 words): who founded the company, when, and what problem they set out to solve. Be specific — "In 2014, our founder spent six months unable to find a non-toxic candle that actually smelled good" is more compelling than "We are passionate about quality candles." Second, the Mission and Values (80-100 words): state what drives decisions today. Tie values to customer impact: "We test every ingredient against EU safety standards — even though we are US-based — because your trust is not optional." Third, the Social Proof section: team size, products shipped, years in business, media features. Use concrete numbers: "147,000 orders shipped to 38 countries." Fourth, the Team or Workshop: a photo of real people or your workspace. Stock photos destroy credibility on this page specifically. For SEO, target your brand name plus "about," "story," and "who we are" keywords. Include schema markup (Organization type) with founding date, founders, and location. Link to your Contact page, any press coverage, and your best-performing category. End with a CTA that transitions the visitor from learning to shopping: "Now that you know our story — explore the collection."',
        'tags'        => ['about-us', 'brand-story', 'trust', 'organization-schema', 'founding'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'cms_pages',
        'subcategory' => 'contact_page',
        'title'       => 'Contact Page Optimization for SEO and Conversions',
        'content'     => 'The Contact page needs to serve three visitor types: the pre-sale question asker, the post-sale support seeker, and the business inquiry sender. Segment pathways clearly: a "Questions about a product?" section linking to live chat or email, a "Need help with an order?" section with order-lookup functionality, and a "Press, wholesale, or partnerships?" section with a dedicated form or email. Each pathway reduces friction and routes messages to the right team. For local SEO, include your full business address formatted consistently with your Google Business Profile, embedded Google Map, phone number with click-to-call markup, and business hours. Use LocalBusiness schema markup with all these details. If you do not have a physical storefront, list your registered business address and note "Online only — no walk-in location." Include expected response times: "We reply to all emails within 4 business hours" manages expectations and builds trust. For the form itself, ask only essential fields — name, email, subject dropdown, message. Every additional field reduces submissions. Place your social media links here but do not make them the primary contact method; customers contacting you have a problem, and social media support feels public and uncertain. Add a brief FAQ section (3-5 questions) below the form to deflect common queries: "Where is my order?" with a tracking link saves both parties time.',
        'tags'        => ['contact', 'local-seo', 'support', 'schema', 'form-optimization', 'response-time'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'cms_pages',
        'subcategory' => 'shipping_returns',
        'title'       => 'Shipping and Returns Policy Pages for SEO',
        'content'     => 'Shipping and returns pages rank for high-intent queries like "[brand] shipping cost," "[brand] return policy," and "[brand] free shipping." Optimize them as you would any landing page. Structure the shipping page with clear sections: Domestic Shipping (methods, costs, delivery times in a table), International Shipping (countries served, customs note, delivery estimates), Free Shipping Threshold (make this prominent — it directly affects AOV), and Order Processing Time ("Orders placed before 2 PM EST ship same day"). Use a table format for shipping options: Method | Cost | Delivery Time | Tracking. For the returns page, lead with confidence: "We accept returns within 30 days, no questions asked." Then detail the process in numbered steps: (1) Start your return at [link], (2) Print the prepaid label, (3) Drop off at any UPS location, (4) Refund processed within 5 business days of receipt. Specify what is not returnable (personalized items, final sale) upfront — hiding exclusions in fine print generates chargebacks and angry reviews. Include your exchange process separately. For SEO, target "[brand] shipping policy" and "[brand] returns" as primary keywords. Add FAQ schema for the most common questions: "How long do refunds take?" "Can I exchange for a different size?" These pages build trust at a critical moment — the buyer is evaluating risk before committing to purchase.',
        'tags'        => ['shipping', 'returns', 'policy', 'trust', 'faq-schema', 'conversion'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'cms_pages',
        'subcategory' => 'faq_page',
        'title'       => 'FAQ Page with Schema Markup for Featured Snippets',
        'content'     => 'A well-structured FAQ page can dominate Google\'s "People Also Ask" boxes and featured snippets. Start by auditing real customer questions from support tickets, live chat logs, review Q&As, and Google Search Console queries. Group questions into logical sections: Ordering & Payment, Shipping & Delivery, Returns & Exchanges, Product Information, and Account & Privacy. Write answers that are concise but complete — aim for 40-80 words per answer. The first sentence should directly answer the question (this is what Google pulls for snippets), followed by supporting detail. Example: "Q: Do you ship internationally? A: Yes, we ship to over 40 countries worldwide. International orders typically arrive within 7-14 business days. Customs duties and import taxes are the responsibility of the buyer and are not included in our shipping charges. See our full international shipping guide for country-specific details." Implement FAQPage schema markup using JSON-LD — wrap each question in a Question entity and each answer in an AcceptedAnswer entity. Limit schema-marked questions to 10-15 per page; Google may ignore pages with excessive FAQ schema. Keep answers factual and avoid promotional language within schema-marked content — Google guidelines discourage using FAQ schema for advertising. Update your FAQ quarterly based on new question trends. Link answers to relevant pages: the shipping answer links to the shipping policy, the sizing answer links to the size guide. This internal linking strengthens your entire site structure.',
        'tags'        => ['faq', 'schema-markup', 'featured-snippets', 'people-also-ask', 'support', 'structured-data'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'cms_pages',
        'subcategory' => 'blog_content',
        'title'       => 'Blog-Style Content Strategy for E-commerce SEO',
        'content'     => 'Blog content for e-commerce should target informational queries that sit one step above purchase intent — "how to choose a coffee grinder" rather than "buy coffee grinder." The goal is to capture the researcher and guide them toward your products through genuine expertise. Map each blog post to a category page: the coffee grinder guide links to your grinder category, the "best exercises for lower back pain" post links to your lumbar support products. Three high-performing post types for e-commerce: (1) Buying Guides — "The Complete Guide to Choosing a [Product Type] in 2026" — target comparison keywords and link to filtered category views. (2) How-To Posts — "How to Season a Cast Iron Skillet" — target instructional queries and feature your products as the tool. (3) Roundup Posts — "10 Home Office Upgrades Under $50" — target gift and idea keywords, link to individual products. Every post needs a clear content brief before writing: target keyword, search intent, word count (1,200-2,000 for guides, 600-1,000 for how-tos), internal links to product or category pages, and a CTA (product recommendation, newsletter signup, or category browse). Avoid thin posts under 500 words — they rarely rank and dilute your site quality. Publish on a consistent schedule (weekly or biweekly) rather than bursts of 10 posts followed by months of silence. Update top-performing posts annually with fresh data and current products.',
        'tags'        => ['blog', 'content-marketing', 'informational-intent', 'buying-guide', 'how-to', 'internal-linking'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'cms_pages',
        'subcategory' => 'size_guide',
        'title'       => 'Size Guide Pages That Reduce Returns and Boost SEO',
        'content'     => 'Size guide pages are SEO opportunities disguised as utility. They rank for "[brand] size chart," "[product type] size guide," and measurement queries, while directly reducing your return rate. Structure the page with three components: a visual measurement diagram (illustrated, not photographed, for clarity), a conversion table (US, UK, EU sizes side by side), and a "How to Measure" section with step-by-step instructions. Use specific, actionable guidance: "Wrap a soft tape measure around the fullest part of your chest, keeping the tape level. The tape should be snug but not compressing — you should be able to slide one finger underneath." Include a "Between Sizes?" recommendation: "If you are between sizes, we recommend sizing up for a relaxed fit or staying true for a fitted look." Add a brand-specific fit note: "Our sizing runs slightly small compared to standard US sizing. If you wear a Medium in most brands, consider ordering a Large." For products with multiple fit options (slim, regular, relaxed), create a visual comparison showing the same model in each fit. Implement the page as a standalone CMS page and link to it from every relevant product page. For international stores, auto-detect the visitor\'s region and default to the appropriate sizing system. Track which size guide pages have the highest exit rates — these indicate confusing content that needs rewriting.',
        'tags'        => ['size-guide', 'sizing', 'returns-reduction', 'measurement', 'fit', 'conversion-table'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'cms_pages',
        'subcategory' => 'loyalty_program',
        'title'       => 'Loyalty and Rewards Program Page Content',
        'content'     => 'Your loyalty program page must answer "What do I get?" within the first five seconds. Lead with the value proposition in concrete terms: "Earn 1 point per dollar spent. Redeem 100 points for $10 off your next order." Avoid vague promises like "exclusive rewards" — specificity drives enrollment. Structure the page in three tiers: How It Works (3 numbered steps: sign up, earn, redeem), Benefits by Tier (if applicable, use a comparison table showing Silver, Gold, Platinum perks), and FAQ (how to check balance, expiration policy, combining with other offers). Visualize the earning journey: "Your $150 average order earns 150 points. After 3 orders, you have earned $45 in rewards." This math makes the value tangible. List all earning opportunities: purchases, reviews, referrals, birthday bonus, social follows. For SEO, target "[brand] rewards program," "[brand] loyalty points," and "how to earn [brand] points." Use HowTo schema for the enrollment steps. Include testimonials from real members: "I have earned $230 in rewards this year just from my regular orders — Sarah K." Add a persistent CTA: "Join free — start earning today." Address the most common objection (cost/commitment) upfront: "No membership fee. No minimum purchase. No catch." Link to the enrollment form with minimal fields — email and password should be sufficient for basic membership.',
        'tags'        => ['loyalty', 'rewards', 'points', 'retention', 'enrollment', 'tier-benefits'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'cms_pages',
        'subcategory' => 'sustainability',
        'title'       => 'Sustainability and Ethics Page Content',
        'content'     => 'Sustainability pages have become essential for e-commerce trust, but they must demonstrate rather than declare. Avoid vague claims like "We care about the planet." Instead, provide specific, verifiable commitments: "100% of our packaging is made from post-consumer recycled cardboard. Our shipping poly mailers are compostable and break down in 180 days." Structure the page around concrete pillars: Materials & Sourcing (where your materials come from and how they are produced), Manufacturing (labor practices, factory certifications, carbon footprint data), Packaging & Shipping (material choices, carbon offset programs), and End-of-Life (recycling programs, repair services, take-back initiatives). For each pillar, state the current status and your next goal: "Currently: 72% of our cotton is organic certified. Goal: 100% by 2027." This transparency — including the gap — builds more trust than a perfect-sounding claim. Include third-party certifications with their logos: B Corp, Fair Trade, GOTS, OEKO-TEX, Forest Stewardship Council. Link to full audit reports or certification documents if available. Name your suppliers when possible: "Our leather comes from Conceria Walpier in Tuscany, a gold-rated Leather Working Group tannery." For SEO, target "[brand] sustainability," "ethical [product type]," and "eco-friendly [category]." Update this page annually with progress metrics. A stale sustainability page suggests abandoned commitments.',
        'tags'        => ['sustainability', 'ethics', 'eco-friendly', 'certifications', 'transparency', 'green'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'cms_pages',
        'subcategory' => 'gift_guides',
        'title'       => 'Gift Guide Pages for Seasonal SEO Traffic',
        'content'     => 'Gift guide pages capture high-volume seasonal searches: "gifts for dad," "housewarming gift ideas," "anniversary gifts for her." Create a core set of evergreen guides organized by recipient (gifts for him, her, teens, grandparents, coworkers) and occasion (birthday, wedding, housewarming, holiday, graduation). Each guide should feature 10-20 curated products with a one-sentence editorial rationale: "For the home cook who has every gadget: our Japanese Damascus Steel Chef Knife — because the right blade changes everything." Include a price range filter or organize products by price tier: Under $25, $25-$50, $50-$100, $100+. Each product should link directly to its PDP. Write a 150-250 word introduction for each guide targeting the primary keyword: "Finding the perfect gift for Dad does not have to mean another necktie. Our Father\'s Day gift guide features handpicked items he will actually use — from precision-engineered tools to single-origin coffee subscriptions." Publish seasonal guides 6-8 weeks before the occasion to allow for indexing — a Valentine\'s guide published on February 10th is too late for SEO. Update guides annually with new products while keeping the URL unchanged to preserve accumulated authority. Use breadcrumbs: Home > Gift Guides > Gifts for Dad. Add "Bestseller" or "Staff Pick" badges to highlight top recommendations. These pages generate high engagement, strong internal links, and consistent seasonal traffic year over year.',
        'tags'        => ['gift-guide', 'seasonal', 'holiday', 'curation', 'editorial', 'high-intent'],
