    [
        'category'    => 'cms_pages',
        'subcategory' => 'store_locator',
        'title'       => 'Store Locator and Location Pages for Local SEO',
        'content'     => 'If you have physical retail locations, each store needs a dedicated location page — not just a pin on a map. Each page should include: the full address formatted for LocalBusiness schema, embedded Google Map, phone number with click-to-call, hours of operation (including holiday hours), driving and transit directions from major landmarks, a photo gallery of the actual storefront and interior, and a short description of what makes that location unique ("Our flagship Portland store features a tasting bar and weekend barista workshops"). For the store locator index page, implement a zip-code or city search with geolocation auto-detect as the primary interaction. List locations by state or region below the search for crawlability — search engines cannot interact with a search box, so all locations must be linked via static HTML. Use LocalBusiness schema on each individual location page with geo-coordinates, business type, and parent organization reference. Target location-specific keywords: "[brand] [city] store," "[brand] near me," "[product type] store [city]." Include a "What to Expect" section for each location: "Free parking in the rear lot. Wheelchair accessible. Dog-friendly patio. Curbside pickup available." Add a booking or appointment link if applicable. For online-only stores without physical locations, skip this page entirely — a fake or virtual address hurts local SEO trust signals.',
        'tags'        => ['store-locator', 'local-seo', 'location-pages', 'google-business', 'brick-and-mortar', 'schema'],
