    [
        'category'    => 'homepage_content',
        'subcategory' => 'hero_section',
        'title'       => 'Writing Hero Section Copy That Converts',
        'content'     => 'The homepage hero has 3-5 seconds to answer "Am I in the right place?" and "What should I do next?" The headline should be 5-10 words that name the value, not the product: "Cookware That Performs. Prices That Don\'t Punish." is better than "Welcome to Our Cookware Store." Avoid generic welcomes entirely — they waste the most valuable real estate on your site. The subheadline (15-25 words) adds a proof layer: "Professional-grade stainless steel and cast iron, direct from the factory. Free shipping over $75." This combination gives the visitor a reason to stay (quality cookware at fair prices) and a reason to act (free shipping threshold). The CTA button should use action-specific text: "Shop the Collection," "Explore New Arrivals," or "Find Your Size" outperforms generic "Shop Now" by 10-20% in most A/B tests because it tells the visitor what happens next. Use a single primary CTA — two competing buttons split attention and reduce clicks on both. For seasonal heroes, lead with the occasion: "Mother\'s Day Gifts She\'ll Actually Keep" is more compelling than "Spring Sale." Rotate heroes every 2-4 weeks to prevent banner blindness among returning visitors. Test headline variants by measuring click-through to the linked category or landing page. The hero image must complement, not compete with, the text — dark overlay or a natural negative-space area ensures readability.',
        'tags'        => ['hero', 'headline', 'above-fold', 'cta', 'conversion', 'homepage'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'homepage_content',
        'subcategory' => 'value_proposition',
        'title'       => 'Value Proposition Messaging on the Homepage',
        'content'     => 'Below the hero, a value proposition bar (often called a "trust strip") communicates your competitive advantages in scannable form. Use 3-4 short statements with icons: "Free Shipping Over $50" | "30-Day Easy Returns" | "Handmade in the USA" | "100,000+ Happy Customers." Each statement must be concrete and verifiable — avoid vague platitudes like "Quality You Can Trust" or "Customer Satisfaction Guaranteed." Quantify wherever possible: a number is more believable than an adjective. Prioritize the propositions by what your target audience cares most about: price-sensitive shoppers want to see free shipping and sale mentions first; quality-focused shoppers want origin and craftsmanship; anxious first-time buyers want returns policy and reviews count. Test different orderings — the first and last positions in a horizontal strip get the most visual attention. Make each proposition clickable, linking to the relevant page: the shipping statement links to the shipping policy, the reviews statement links to a reviews or testimonials page. On mobile, these should stack vertically or scroll horizontally — do not shrink the font to fit four items on one line. Refresh the propositions seasonally: "Gift Wrapping Available" during holidays, "New Spring Arrivals Weekly" in March. The value proposition strip appears on every page in many stores; if so, keep it in the site header or just below, and ensure it does not push product content below the fold.',
        'tags'        => ['value-proposition', 'trust-strip', 'usp', 'competitive-advantage', 'homepage', 'conversion'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'homepage_content',
        'subcategory' => 'trust_signals',
        'title'       => 'Trust Signal Placement and Content on the Homepage',
        'content'     => 'Trust signals convert skeptical first-time visitors into buyers. Place them strategically throughout the homepage, not clustered in one section. Tier 1 (above the fold): payment security badges (SSL, accepted payment methods), and one headline social proof stat ("Rated 4.8/5 from 23,000+ reviews"). Tier 2 (mid-page): a curated testimonial block with 3 reviews that address different anxieties — quality ("The craftsmanship exceeded my expectations"), service ("Customer support helped me pick the perfect size"), and value ("Worth every penny — I have reordered twice"). Use full names, locations, and verified-purchase badges if available. Photos of real customers increase testimonial credibility by 35%. Tier 3 (lower page): press logos ("As Seen In: Vogue, GQ, NYT Wirecutter"), certifications (BBB, industry-specific), and partnership badges. Avoid cluttering — 3-5 press logos are enough; 15 logos look desperate. For e-commerce specifically, address the three core buying anxieties at appropriate moments: "Is the product quality real?" (reviews and imagery), "Will my payment be safe?" (security badges near any CTA), "What if I do not like it?" (returns policy near add-to-cart areas). Never use fake testimonials or inflated numbers — savvy shoppers verify, and the trust damage from being caught is irreversible. Update testimonials quarterly to keep them fresh and representative of your current product line.',
        'tags'        => ['trust', 'social-proof', 'reviews', 'testimonials', 'security', 'press'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'homepage_content',
        'subcategory' => 'featured_categories',
        'title'       => 'Writing Featured Category Descriptions on the Homepage',
        'content'     => 'Homepage category callouts guide visitors who arrived without a specific product in mind. Use 3-6 featured category blocks, each with a strong image, a short heading (3-5 words), and one line of descriptive copy (10-20 words). The heading should name the category and hint at the experience: "Kitchen Essentials" is functional; "Outfit Your Kitchen" is actionable. The one-line description should answer "Why browse this category?": "Handcrafted tools and small-batch ingredients for cooks who taste the difference." Avoid generic descriptions like "Browse our selection of kitchen products." Each category block should link to the corresponding category page, not a filtered search. Order the blocks by business priority: highest-margin or seasonal categories first, clearance or niche categories last. On mobile, display as a scrollable card row or a 2-column grid — never stack 6 full-width blocks vertically, as this pushes remaining content unreachably far down. Rotate featured categories based on seasonality, inventory levels, and traffic trends. For new stores with limited categories, use broader groupings ("For Her," "For Home," "Under $50") that span multiple product types. Add a "View All Categories" link for visitors who do not find their interest in the featured set. Track click-through rates on each block — a category with low clicks needs either a better image, a more compelling description, or replacement with a higher-interest category.',
        'tags'        => ['featured-categories', 'homepage', 'navigation', 'merchandising', 'curation', 'click-through'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'homepage_content',
        'subcategory' => 'newsletter_signup',
        'title'       => 'Homepage Newsletter Signup Copy That Converts',
        'content'     => 'The newsletter signup block is a value exchange — the visitor gives their email, and you must articulate exactly what they receive. "Sign up for our newsletter" converts at roughly 1%. "Get 15% off your first order + weekly style tips" converts at 5-8%. Lead with the incentive, then name the content value. Structure: Headline (the offer) + Subheadline (what to expect) + Single email field + CTA button. Example: Headline: "15% Off Your First Order." Subheadline: "Plus new arrivals, styling tips, and member-only sales every Thursday." CTA: "Send My Code" (not "Subscribe" — the word "subscribe" triggers commitment anxiety). Place the signup block in the lower third of the homepage or as a timed/exit-intent popup — avoid interrupting the shopping flow immediately on arrival. For the popup variant, delay by at least 10 seconds or 50% scroll depth. Never use a generic "Submit" button — mirror the user\'s motivation in the CTA text: "Get My Discount," "Join the Club," "Send My Free Guide." Address privacy briefly near the form: "We send one email per week. Unsubscribe anytime." This reduces friction. After signup, the confirmation page should immediately deliver the promised code and suggest a category to browse: "Here is your code: WELCOME15. Shop our bestsellers now." Track signup rate by placement (footer vs. popup vs. inline block) and optimize the lowest performer.',
        'tags'        => ['newsletter', 'email-signup', 'lead-capture', 'incentive', 'popup', 'conversion'],
    ],


    // =========================================================================
    // INDUSTRY-SPECIFIC CONTENT (15 entries)
    // =========================================================================

    [
        'category'    => 'industry_specific',
        'subcategory' => 'fashion_apparel',
        'title'       => 'Fashion and Apparel Store Content Strategy',
        'content'     => 'Fashion e-commerce content must balance aspiration with information. Product descriptions should lead with the occasion or lifestyle ("A wear-everywhere midi dress for workdays, date nights, and weekend brunch") and follow with tactile fabric details and fit guidance. Use "style notes" as a content format: 2-3 sentences from a stylist on how to wear the piece, what to pair it with, and which body types it flatters. This format builds authority and helps shoppers visualize. Category pages need seasonal updates more than any other industry — "Spring/Summer 2026 Dresses" signals freshness. Use editorial language: "This season leans into relaxed tailoring, sun-faded palettes, and textured linens." Homepage content should mirror a magazine cover: bold imagery, minimal text, one clear message per visual. Create dedicated "Shop the Look" pages that style complete outfits and link to each component product — these pages capture "outfit idea" searches and increase items per order. Size inclusivity content matters: if you carry extended sizes, say it prominently rather than burying it in a filter. Trend-forward stores should publish weekly "New Arrivals" or "Editor\'s Picks" content to drive repeat visits. Use user-generated content (customer photos) on product pages and a branded hashtag gallery on the homepage — social proof is uniquely powerful in fashion because shoppers want to see real bodies wearing the clothes.',
        'tags'        => ['fashion', 'apparel', 'styling', 'seasonal', 'editorial', 'shop-the-look'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'industry_specific',
        'subcategory' => 'electronics_tech',
        'title'       => 'Electronics and Tech Store Content Strategy',
        'content'     => 'Tech store content must serve two distinct journeys: the informed buyer who knows exactly what they want (spec-comparison, compatibility check, price confirm, buy) and the researcher who needs guidance (what is the difference between these models, which one suits my needs). For informed buyers, product pages need thorough spec tables, "In the Box" lists, compatibility notes, and firmware/software version details. For researchers, create comparison pages: "AirPods Pro 3 vs. Sony WF-1000XM6: Which Earbuds Win?" with a structured breakdown by category (sound quality, battery, comfort, price). These pages rank for high-volume versus queries. Category descriptions should acknowledge the buying complexity: "Choosing a laptop depends on whether you prioritize portability, performance, or price — and how you weight each. Our collection includes ultrabooks for travelers, workstations for creators, and value laptops for everyday tasks." Use "Buying Guides" as a core content type, updated quarterly as new models launch. Product descriptions must translate specs into outcomes — the buyer does not care about "120 Hz refresh rate" nearly as much as "Scrolling feels buttery smooth, and fast-moving game scenes stay sharp." Include setup difficulty and ecosystem notes: "Works with Alexa and Google Home; no Apple HomeKit support as of Q1 2026." Returns messaging is critical in tech — highlight restocking fees, opened-box policies, and warranty clearly. Trust signals should include authorized-reseller badges and manufacturer warranty details.',
        'tags'        => ['electronics', 'tech', 'comparison', 'specs', 'buying-guide', 'compatibility'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'industry_specific',
        'subcategory' => 'home_garden',
        'title'       => 'Home and Garden Store Content Strategy',
        'content'     => 'Home and garden stores sell transformation — the customer is buying the version of their space they want to live in. Product descriptions should place the item in a room: "This 8x10 hand-knotted wool rug anchors a living room with warmth and texture — rich enough for a formal dining space, durable enough for a household with kids and pets." Include room-size recommendations: "Best for rooms 12x14 feet and larger; for smaller spaces, see our 5x7 version." For furniture, always specify assembly requirements, delivery method (doorstep vs. white-glove), and return logistics — returning a sofa is a major operation, and the customer wants to know the process upfront. Category pages benefit from room-based navigation ("Shop by Room: Living Room, Bedroom, Kitchen, Outdoor") in addition to product-type categories. Seasonal content rotates heavily: outdoor furniture and garden tools peak in spring, cozy textiles and lighting in fall. Create "Room Makeover" or "Designer Picks" editorial content that bundles products into a cohesive vision — "A Scandinavian-Minimalist Living Room for Under $2,000." Include maintenance content: "How to Care for Teak Outdoor Furniture" or "The Best Indoor Plants for Low Light" — these guides capture informational queries and position your store as an authority. User-generated room photos ("See it in real homes") are enormously effective — customers cannot gauge scale from studio photography alone.',
        'tags'        => ['home', 'garden', 'furniture', 'room-design', 'seasonal', 'care-guides'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'industry_specific',
        'subcategory' => 'food_beverage',
        'title'       => 'Food and Beverage Store Content Strategy',
        'content'     => 'Food and beverage e-commerce faces a unique challenge: the customer cannot taste before buying. Your content must be the tasting experience. Product descriptions need layered sensory writing — aroma, flavor profile, texture, finish: "This aged balsamic opens with tart cherry and fig, glides over the palate with a syrupy viscosity, and finishes with a warm, caramelized sweetness that lingers." Include pairing suggestions as a standard section: "Drizzle over burrata and ripe tomatoes, stir into a pan reduction, or finish roasted strawberries." Origin storytelling justifies premium pricing: "Sourced from a single estate in Modena where the Leonardi family has been producing balsamic since 1871." Category pages should organize by use case alongside type: "For Cooking," "For Finishing," "For Gifting." Dietary filters must be prominent and accurate — one mislabeled allergen can be a health crisis and a legal liability. Create recipe content that features your products: a blog post for "3 Summer Salad Dressings" with your olive oil as the star ingredient captures informational searches and drives product discovery. Subscription offerings should be explained thoroughly: frequency options, skip/pause flexibility, and savings versus one-time purchase. Shipping content must address perishability: "Ships in insulated packaging with gel ice packs. Arrives within 2 days for guaranteed freshness." Include shelf-life and storage instructions on every product page.',
        'tags'        => ['food', 'beverage', 'sensory', 'pairing', 'recipes', 'subscription', 'perishable'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'industry_specific',
        'subcategory' => 'health_beauty',
        'title'       => 'Health and Beauty Store Content Strategy',
        'content'     => 'Beauty e-commerce content must educate and reassure — shoppers are putting products on their body and need to trust both the brand and the ingredients. Every product page needs an ingredient list with key actives highlighted and explained: "Niacinamide (Vitamin B3) — reduces the appearance of pores and evens skin tone over 4-6 weeks." Include a "Free From" list if relevant: no parabens, sulfates, phthalates, artificial fragrance. Specify skin type suitability clearly — "Best for dry to normal skin; those with oily or acne-prone skin should try our Gel Moisturizer instead." This honest routing builds trust and prevents returns. Create routine-based content that links products together: "Your 4-Step Evening Routine: Cleanse with [link], treat with [link], moisturize with [link], protect with [link]." This format increases multi-product purchases and positions you as an authority. Category descriptions should address the concern, not just the product type: "Dark Spot Correctors" should read "Target hyperpigmentation from sun exposure, hormones, or post-acne marks with serums and treatments clinically shown to brighten and even skin tone." Include before/after timelines (not photos, which face regulatory scrutiny): "Most customers see visible improvement within 28 days of consistent use." Shade-matching guidance is critical for complexion products — include a quiz, virtual try-on tool, or detailed shade descriptions: "Warm Beige — medium depth with golden-olive undertones; best for those who tan easily." Certifications (cruelty-free, vegan, dermatologist-tested) should appear on every product page, not just a dedicated page.',
        'tags'        => ['beauty', 'skincare', 'health', 'ingredients', 'routine', 'shade-matching', 'clean-beauty'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'industry_specific',
        'subcategory' => 'sports_outdoor',
        'title'       => 'Sports and Outdoor Store Content Strategy',
        'content'     => 'Sports and outdoor shoppers are buying performance, safety, and experience. They are often researching extensively before purchase and comparing across specialist retailers. Product descriptions must speak the language of the specific activity — a trail runner and a road runner use different vocabulary and care about different features. Name the intended use in the first sentence: "A 35L alpine climbing pack built for single-day technical routes in variable conditions." Include performance conditions: "Waterproof to 10,000 mm water column; seams fully taped." Use activity-specific metrics: "Stack height: 29mm heel / 21mm forefoot. Drop: 8mm." Category pages should organize by activity first ("Hiking," "Climbing," "Trail Running," "Camping") and product type second — an outdoor enthusiast identifies by activity, not by "Footwear" generically. Create seasonal preparation content: "Getting Ready for Backpacking Season: The 10 Essentials Checklist" with each essential linking to your products. Leverage athlete or guide testimonials: "Tested by Sarah Chen during her PCT thru-hike — 2,653 miles in the same pair." Include care and repair content — outdoor enthusiasts value longevity: "How to Reapply DWR Coating to Your Rain Jacket" keeps customers engaged and builds brand loyalty. Sizing and fit guidance is critical for performance gear — a half-size error on a climbing shoe changes everything. Include activity-specific sizing advice: "Most climbers size down 0.5-1 full size from street shoes for precision on technical routes; size true for all-day comfort on moderate grades."',
        'tags'        => ['sports', 'outdoor', 'performance', 'activity-based', 'gear', 'adventure'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'industry_specific',
        'subcategory' => 'jewelry_accessories',
        'title'       => 'Jewelry and Accessories Store Content Strategy',
        'content'     => 'Jewelry e-commerce content must bridge the gap between screen and showroom — customers cannot feel weight, see sparkle, or try on pieces. Product descriptions should evoke the physical experience: "This 18K rose gold bangle has a satisfying heft — 22 grams of solid metal that catches light with every gesture." Use precise gemological language for fine jewelry: "Center stone: 1.2 ct round brilliant diamond, G color, VS1 clarity, Excellent cut." For fashion jewelry, focus on design narrative and versatility: "Inspired by brutalist architecture — an angular cuff that transforms a plain white tee into a statement." Photography must be exceptional, but descriptions should add what photos cannot: weight, how the clasp works, how the piece sounds (a charm bracelet jingles), and how it layers with other pieces. Category pages should offer navigation by occasion (Wedding, Everyday, Date Night), by type (Rings, Necklaces, Earrings), and by price range. Create educational content: "The 4Cs of Diamond Buying" or "Gold Karat Guide: 10K vs. 14K vs. 18K" — these guides capture research queries and position you as a trusted authority. Gifting is a massive driver — at least 40% of jewelry purchases are gifts. Every product page should have a "Gift This" option and mention packaging: "Arrives in a velvet-lined magnetic box with a hand-tied ribbon." Include care instructions: "Remove before swimming; store in the included anti-tarnish pouch." For custom or personalized pieces, clearly explain the process, timeline, and any return limitations.',
        'tags'        => ['jewelry', 'accessories', 'fine-jewelry', 'fashion-jewelry', 'gifting', 'gemology'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'industry_specific',
        'subcategory' => 'b2b_wholesale',
        'title'       => 'B2B and Wholesale Store Content Strategy',
        'content'     => 'B2B e-commerce content must serve a buying committee, not a single impulse shopper. Descriptions need to address multiple stakeholders: the end user (does it work?), the procurement manager (is the price competitive? is the vendor reliable?), and the decision-maker (what is the ROI? does it comply with our standards?). Lead with the business outcome: "Reduce warehouse pick-and-pack time by 30% with our automated labeling system" — not "Our label printer features 300 DPI resolution." Include compliance and certification information prominently: ISO standards, OSHA compliance, FDA approval, REACH certification. These are not nice-to-haves in B2B — they are gatekeepers. Provide downloadable spec sheets, SDS documents, and CAD files where relevant — B2B buyers need documents for internal review. Pricing should address volume: show tiered pricing (1-49 units, 50-199, 200+) or a "Request Quote" CTA for custom pricing. Include case studies as product-adjacent content: "How [Company X] Reduced Downtime by 40% Using [Product]" with specific data and a named contact. Category pages should support reordering workflows: "Recently Ordered," "Frequently Bought Together," and quick-add-to-cart functionality. Payment terms content matters: "NET 30 available for approved accounts; apply during checkout." Shipping content should detail freight options, pallet quantities, and lead times for large orders. B2B SEO targets long-tail queries: "industrial label printer for warehouse management" rather than "label printer."',
        'tags'        => ['b2b', 'wholesale', 'procurement', 'compliance', 'volume-pricing', 'case-study'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'industry_specific',
        'subcategory' => 'marketplace',
        'title'       => 'Multi-Brand Marketplace Content Strategy',
        'content'     => 'Marketplaces face a unique content challenge: maintaining a cohesive voice while representing dozens or hundreds of distinct brands. Establish content standards that sellers must meet: minimum description length (150 words), required attributes (size, color, material, origin), banned language (unverifiable superlatives, competitor comparisons, external links), and image requirements (white background, minimum resolution, consistent aspect ratio). Provide sellers with a description template that follows your marketplace\'s structure while allowing brand voice: a required opening sentence format, a required feature block, and a free-form brand story section. For categories, the marketplace (not the seller) should write the category description — this ensures consistent quality and avoids the patchwork effect of seller-written category content. Curate "Editor\'s Picks" and "Staff Favorites" collections where the marketplace voice shines: "Our buying team tasted 47 hot sauces to select these 12 — ranging from mild smoky to face-melting habanero." These editorial moments differentiate your marketplace from a commodity platform. Brand landing pages within the marketplace should include: brand story (written or approved by the brand), logo, key product highlights, and a "Shop All [Brand]" link. For SEO, the marketplace must own the meta titles and descriptions for category and homepage — do not let sellers control page-level metadata. Address trust and authenticity: "Every seller on our marketplace is vetted and verified. All products are guaranteed authentic" with a link to your seller standards page.',
        'tags'        => ['marketplace', 'multi-brand', 'seller-standards', 'curation', 'editorial', 'authenticity'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'industry_specific',
        'subcategory' => 'luxury_premium',
        'title'       => 'Luxury and Premium Brand Store Content Strategy',
        'content'     => 'Luxury e-commerce content operates on entirely different principles than mass-market retail. The goal is not to convince — it is to confirm the buyer\'s self-image and reward their taste. Never sell; curate. Never discount; celebrate value. Product descriptions read like editorial prose, not feature lists: "The Pemberton Briefcase in cognac bridle leather — hand-stitched by a single artisan over three days, with brass hardware cast from 19th-century molds. It does not carry your work. It elevates it." Avoid bullet points — they feel transactional. Use flowing paragraphs of 2-3 sentences. Include provenance details that signal rarity: "Limited to 200 pieces per season" or "Made from leather sourced from a single Scottish tannery that has operated since 1862." Photography should be editorial quality with lifestyle context — a watch on a wrist at a linen-draped table, not floating on white. Category pages should feel like gallery rooms: minimal text, maximum visual impact, with descriptions that frame the collection theme: "The Autumn Archive: layers of cashmere, textured tweed, and burnished leather, drawn from the muted palette of the Scottish Highlands." Avoid urgency tactics (countdown timers, "Only 3 left!") — they cheapen the experience. Instead, use subtle scarcity: "This piece is produced in limited quantities. Contact our advisory team to confirm availability." Customer service language should be "advisory" or "concierge," not "support." Include white-glove service descriptions: "Complimentary gift wrapping in our signature box. Handwritten note included upon request." Content should never reference competitors, sales, or price-for-value — price is simply the entry point to an experience.',
        'tags'        => ['luxury', 'premium', 'editorial', 'provenance', 'craftsmanship', 'exclusivity'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'industry_specific',
        'subcategory' => 'kids_baby',
        'title'       => 'Kids and Baby Store Content Strategy',
        'content'     => 'Parents shopping for children are driven by safety first, developmental value second, and delight third. Every product description should address safety before anything else: "CPSC-compliant and JPMA-certified. Free from BPA, phthalates, and lead paint. Designed and tested for ages 6 months and up." Follow safety with developmental benefit: "The stacking rings teach color recognition, size sequencing, and hand-eye coordination — your pediatrician would approve." Then deliver the fun: "Bright, chunky rings that babies love to grab, mouth, and knock over (and over, and over)." Age ranges must be precise and prominent — a parent buying for a 9-month-old needs instant confirmation. Include milestone context: "Ideal for the sitting-up-unassisted stage (typically 6-9 months)." Material descriptions should be thorough and parent-friendly: "Organic cotton muslin, GOTS-certified, pre-washed for softness. Machine washable — because you will need to wash it often." Category pages should offer age-based navigation ("0-6 Months," "6-12 Months," "1-2 Years," "3-5 Years") alongside product-type categories. Create content that helps overwhelmed new parents: "First Baby Essentials Checklist" or "What Size Does My Baby Need?" These guides capture high-volume informational queries and build long-term brand affinity. Registry functionality and content should be prominent: "Create your baby registry — share a single link with your family." For clothing, include growth-friendly sizing notes: "Designed with 2 inches of cuff roll-up room to last an extra growth spurt." Gift packaging messaging is important — many purchases are gifts: "Arrives in a keepsake-worthy box. Gift receipt included."',
        'tags'        => ['kids', 'baby', 'parenting', 'safety', 'developmental', 'age-appropriate', 'registry'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'industry_specific',
        'subcategory' => 'pet_supplies',
        'title'       => 'Pet Supplies Store Content Strategy',
        'content'     => 'Pet owners are emotionally invested buyers — they are shopping for a family member who cannot communicate preferences. Product descriptions must address both the pet\'s needs and the owner\'s concerns. For food: lead with the health benefit ("Supports joint health in senior dogs with glucosamine and omega-3 fatty acids"), follow with ingredient quality ("Real deboned chicken is the first ingredient — no corn, wheat, or soy fillers"), and include feeding guidelines by weight. For toys: specify durability level honestly — "Built for moderate chewers. Not recommended for power chewers — see our Indestructible line for pit bulls and heavy chewers." This honesty prevents returns and builds trust. Safety is paramount: "Non-toxic, food-grade silicone. No small parts that can be swallowed." Category pages should offer species-first navigation (Dog, Cat, Bird, Fish) with breed or size sub-navigation for dogs. Create breed-specific content: "Best Toys for Golden Retrievers" or "Nutrition Guide for Senior Cats" — these capture highly specific searches with strong purchase intent. Include your veterinary advisory board or nutritionist credentials if you have them — pet food is a trust-heavy purchase. Subscription content is huge in pet supplies because food and litter are repeat purchases: "Subscribe and save 20% — delivered every 4, 6, or 8 weeks. Skip or cancel anytime." Weight and quantity information must be crystal clear — pet owners calculate cost-per-day. Include product photos with real pets for scale and appeal, and encourage customer photos: "Share a photo of your pup with their new toy using #[brandname]."',
        'tags'        => ['pets', 'dog', 'cat', 'pet-food', 'safety', 'breed-specific', 'subscription'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'industry_specific',
        'subcategory' => 'automotive_parts',
        'title'       => 'Automotive Parts Store Content Strategy',
        'content'     => 'Automotive parts e-commerce lives and dies on fitment accuracy. The single most important content element is a clear, trustworthy "This fits your vehicle" confirmation. Implement a Year-Make-Model-Engine selector and display compatibility status prominently on every product page: "Confirmed fit: 2019-2023 Toyota RAV4, 2.5L 4-Cylinder." Product descriptions should lead with the OEM part number and cross-references: "Replaces OEM part #04465-42200. Cross-references: Bosch BC1211, Wagner OEX1211." Follow with material and performance specs: "Semi-metallic compound rated for 45,000 miles. Includes stainless steel hardware and synthetic lubricant." Technical buyers in this space want exact specifications — do not simplify or omit them. Include installation difficulty level: "DIY-friendly. Requires basic hand tools and approximately 45 minutes per axle. See our installation video." Link to installation content — video tutorials and PDF instructions are high-value content assets that capture "how to replace [part] [vehicle]" searches. Category pages should be vehicle-centric: "2022 Honda Civic Parts" with subcategories for Brakes, Engine, Suspension, Electrical, etc. Create maintenance schedule content: "2020 Toyota Camry Maintenance Schedule — recommended service intervals and parts list." Include warranty information prominently: "Lifetime limited warranty. If it fails, we replace it — no proration." Condition descriptions must be exact: "New — OEM specification" or "Remanufactured — tested to OE standards with new seals and bearings." Returns policy for parts requires special attention: "Unused, uninstalled parts accepted within 60 days. Electrical components are non-returnable once installed."',
        'tags'        => ['automotive', 'parts', 'fitment', 'oem', 'installation', 'vehicle-compatibility'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'industry_specific',
        'subcategory' => 'office_supplies',
        'title'       => 'Office Supplies Store Content Strategy',
        'content'     => 'Office supply shoppers are efficiency-driven — they want to find, confirm compatibility, order, and get back to work. Product descriptions should be concise, spec-forward, and focused on compatibility: "Compatible with HP LaserJet Pro M404 series, M304 series, and MFP M428 series. Yields approximately 3,000 pages at 5% coverage." Lead with the compatibility line because it is the first thing the buyer needs confirmed. Follow with the value metric: "12-pack of ballpoint pens — $0.58 per pen. Writes smoothly for 1.4 km of line length." Office buyers think in cost-per-unit, especially in B2B contexts. For furniture and equipment (standing desks, ergonomic chairs, monitors), borrow from the furniture playbook but emphasize the work-performance benefit: "The adjustable monitor arm reduces neck strain during 8-hour workdays by positioning your screen at eye level." Include BIFMA certification for furniture, ENERGY STAR for electronics, and FSC certification for paper products — office managers and procurement teams look for these. Category pages should support bulk ordering with quantity discounts visible: "1-4 boxes: $32.99 | 5-9 boxes: $29.99 | 10+: $26.99." Create "Office Starter Kit" or "Work From Home Essentials" bundle pages — these capture broad search queries from businesses setting up new employees. For SEO, target specific product compatibility queries: "HP M404 toner cartridge" or "Brother TN-760 compatible." These high-intent queries convert well. Delivery speed messaging is critical — offices need supplies now, not next week: "Order by 3 PM for next-day delivery" should be prominent.',
        'tags'        => ['office', 'supplies', 'b2b', 'compatibility', 'bulk-ordering', 'ergonomic'],
    ],

    [
        'category'    => 'industry_specific',
        'subcategory' => 'arts_crafts',
        'title'       => 'Arts and Crafts Store Content Strategy',
        'content'     => 'Arts and crafts shoppers are a mix of beginners seeking guidance and experienced makers seeking specific materials. Product descriptions must serve both by layering information: lead with what the product is and what it is best for ("A professional-grade acrylic paint set in 24 colors — rich pigmentation, smooth consistency, and archival quality for canvas, wood, and mixed-media work"), then specify the technical details experienced users need ("Lightfastness rating: I-II. Pigment load: high. Viscosity: heavy body. Single-pigment formulations where noted"). Include project suggestions for beginners: "Start with our color-mixing guide to learn how these 24 colors expand into hundreds of shades." Create skill-level indicators on product pages: Beginner, Intermediate, Advanced — this helps new crafters avoid frustration and helps experienced ones skip beginner supplies. Category pages should navigate by medium (Painting, Drawing, Fiber Arts, Paper Crafts, Sculpting) and by project type (Home Decor Projects, Gift Making, Kids\' Crafts, Fine Art). Tutorial and project content is the backbone of crafts store SEO: "How to Paint a Sunset in Acrylics" or "Beginner Macrame Wall Hanging Tutorial" — these posts drive organic traffic and naturally feature your products. Include a materials list in each tutorial that links to the products used. Community content is powerful: feature customer projects ("Makers Spotlight"), host virtual workshops, and maintain a project gallery. For subscription boxes (monthly craft kits), describe the unboxing experience and the finished project: "This month\'s kit includes everything you need to create a hand-bound leather journal — pre-cut leather, waxed thread, needles, and step-by-step instructions." Highlight non-toxicity for products that may be used by children or in poorly ventilated spaces: "AP-certified non-toxic. Safe for classroom use."',
